docs.abstract: In announcing the forced resignation, a city agency confirmed that leaked disciplinary records of the officer who placed Mr. Garner in a fatal chokehold, were authentic.
docs.snippet: In announcing the forced resignation, a city agency confirmed that leaked disciplinary records of the officer who placed Mr. Garner in a fatal chokehold, were authentic.
docs.lead_paragraph: A New York City agency charged with investigating police wrongdoing on Thursday forced an employee to resign after discovering that the employee had leaked the disciplinary history of the officer who placed Eric Garner in a fatal chokehold. The agency also confirmed for the first time that the records, which showed that the officer faced no stronger punishment for abusing his authority than retraining and the loss of two vacation days, were authentic.

headline.main: Employee Accused of Records Leak in Eric Garner Case Resigns
headline.print_headline: Employee Forced Out for Leaking Officer’s File

docs.lead_paragraph: The debate over police violence in America is often framed as Black Lives Matter versus Blue Lives Matter. “Shots Fired,” a new 10-episode series on Wednesdays on Fox, starts with a shooter whose life is both black and blue.

headline.main: Review: ‘Shots Fired’ Complicates Black, White and Blue
headline.print_headline: A Divide Refracted in Blue, Black and White

docs.abstract: The murder of a black man in New York reminds a Baltimore neighborhood of its own complicated racial history.
docs.snippet: The murder of a black man in New York reminds a Baltimore neighborhood of its own complicated racial history.
docs.lead_paragraph: BALTIMORE — Under a gloomy sky, a crowd of a few dozen people assembled in the yard outside a stone church, a mostly white group who carried posters and wore T-shirts with messages like “Black Lives Matter,” “Stay Woke” and, simply, “BMORE Kind.” They had come on a Saturday evening to mourn a man they did not know, killed some 200 miles from here.

headline.main: Baltimoreans Mourn a Man Said to Have Been Killed by Their Neighbor
headline.print_headline: Baltimoreans Mourn a Victim in New York

docs.lead_paragraph: Blue lives matter. That is, in essence, what Attorney General Jeff Sessions has been saying since he took office, promising to protect the lives of police officers, stop undermining them as (he implied) the Obama administration had, and let them get back to enforcing law and order.

headline.main: A Debate: Should the Justice Department Police the Police?

docs.abstract: Suggested reading from critics and editors at The New York Times.
docs.snippet: Suggested reading from critics and editors at The New York Times.
docs.lead_paragraph: This week, we’ve got a number of books on our list that are certain to get people talking. Cordelia Fine’s latest, “Testosterone Rex,” addresses head on some of the sexism that poses as neuroscience. Barry Friedman’s important new book, “Unwarranted,” takes on the volatile question of how to address abusive policing. And Angie Thomas’s “The Hate U Give” offers teenage readers a way to look at the Black Lives Matter movement. For sheer fun and entertainment? I recommend Bill Schutt’s “Cannibalism.” As readers will discover, that’s not as strange as it sounds. Bon appetit.

headline.main: 10 New Books We Recommend This Week
headline.print_headline: Editors’ Choice | Staff Picks From the Book Review

docs.lead_paragraph: Soon after Eric Garner died in an encounter with police officers on Staten Island in July 2014, New York City began fighting to shield the disciplinary records of the officer whose chokehold led to the death. In the past, the city had allowed the release of some details on officer discipline.
